2.00	Fossil_fuel_electrical_generation	Fossil-fuel power station	A fossil-fuel power station is a power station that burns fossil fuels such as coal, natural gas or petroleum (oil) to produce electricity. Central station fossil-fuel power plants are designed on a large scale for continuous operation. In many countries, such plants provide most of the electrical energy used.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/SilverLakeRPU.jpg/220px-SilverLakeRPU.jpg
